The paper deals with algorithms for computing the generalized Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT) over finite groups, which is a topic that falls under the umbrella of information theory (cs.IT). The algorithm also involves techniques from computational geometry (cs.CG) and numerical analysis (cs.NA) to optimize the computation. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of group theory and combinatorics (cs.DM) to analyze the complexity of the algorithm. Finally, the paper presents experimental results that involve large-scale computations, which suggests that the algorithm may have practical applications in data science (cs.DS).
